rmk:
Breeding in the city of Borlänge year 2021, on the recording at least 5 juvenile Acrocephalus dumetorum utter contact sounds are heard. They are foraging in a field of Solidago virgaurea of about one hectare and are regularly in contact with this rather subdued call. Until the migration takes place in September, they live a hidden life in the meter-high vegetation and are hardly seen at all.

Pictures at link, Acrocephalus dumetorum in Borlänge: fourfold winner and nominee for Wiki Loves Earth 2021 International Contest - Collection of Björn Söderlund:

https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/User:Sw3dPix

Full crystallized song by the Acrocephalus dumetorum that breeds in Åselby, Dalarna. in 2021. The male sings in response to playback "directed" which means that Area X in the brain has high levels of Foxp2 protein. The crystallized song is an expression of that with its oddly slow tempo. It is at the end of the singing period on June 17 in the breeding season so the male has in practice stopped singing. The song contains imitations of Pernis ptilorhynchus and Merops apiaster.

The song is " three-tuned" on at least five occasions in the recording, for determine this you have to study the sonogram in detail because these interwoven song motifs have such a short duration. They appear most clearly in the repeated strange falling song motifs that are heard at the beginning of the recording. The performer sings with three voice tones at the same time, adding the third overtone above the fundamental tone. This is only possible through lateralization and resonant amplification in the syrinx, which gives cause to the overtones in a complex way. Syrinx can physically only create two tones at a time, the self-oscillation or resonance adds to the third sound element.

The slow paced song style, the repetitions with many iterations and the characteristic three or four note sequences with a large difference in pitch between consecutive notes makes me convinced this is Acrocephalus dumetorum.

What makes the bird so interesting is the regularly recurring mimicries of the closely related, equally masterful, mimic Acrocephalus palustris.

Acrocephalus dumetorum and Acrocephalus palustris in part share a common vocabulary of mimicries of European birds, so it's sometimes hard to tell what's original Acrocephalus dumetorum song and what isn't.

On a number of instances though, Acrocephalus dumetorum clearly mimics Acrocephalus palustris producing its own unique syllables, not constituting part of Acrocephalus dumetorum's vocabulary. These are in some cases mimicry of only presumed African birds, but in some case mimicry of known and identified African birds such as Dryoscopus cubla. This would be an excellent example of hypermimicry, a term coined in [Shrike mimicks warbler mimicking shrike](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/20900).

This is the same bird as the one in XC571560.

As timed references still are so unreliable, I won't bother adding any yet. Check out the Forum Topic [Timing test](https://www.xeno-canto.org/442025) for more info on that subject.

The birds favorite spot is a small willowbush close right to an a way for farming. In the back eastern direction is a small young forrest. On the other side is a field with rape with bushes between the field and the way. During the day it has been seen from time to time, but only shortly. The most of the time it hides in the bushes.
Since the June the 15 th it´s observed together with others, that the bird starts singing around clock 23 und continues. With daybreak it continues, but is getting still and seems to stop in the afternoon.

Middleton Lakes RSPB reserve is a 160 hectares nature reserve comprising a mosaic of wetlands, meadows and woodland in the heart of the River Tame Valley. A 'vagrant' Blyth's Reed Warbler in Staffs, UK, and apparently holding territory : singing for second day from same willow and riverside vegetation, at between 1m and 4m from ground. No filtering applied. Description of bird: depending on light bird could appear quite greyish (a dull cold olive brown) or in the sun a bit more rufous brown especially on the primaries and fore crown. It was notably short-winged. It was also long- billed, with the upper mandible darker especially towards tip and its legs were a dark brownish grey. A light supercilium and diffuse pale eye ring gave it a distinctive face pattern. Underparts had a grey buffish wash which became lighter towards the throat and under tail covert areas.

A Marsh Warbler like song in dense scrub.

[SNR 43dB(ISO/ITU)](https://xeno-canto.org/article/275). 

The slow paced song style, the repetitions with many  iterations and the characteristic three or four note sequences with a large difference in pitch between consecutive notes makes me convinced this is *Acrocephalus dumetorum*.

What makes the bird so interesting is the regularly recurring mimicries of the closely related, equally masterful, mimic *Acrocephalus palustris*.

*Acrocephalus dumetorum* and *Acrocephalus palustris* in part share a common vocabulary of mimicries of European birds, so it's sometimes hard to tell what's original  *Acrocephalus dumetorum* song and what isn't.

On a number of instances though, *Acrocephalus dumetorum* clearly mimics *Acrocephalus palustris* producing its own unique syllables, not constituting part of *Acrocephalus dumetorum's* vocabulary. These are in some cases mimicry of only presumed African birds, but in some case mimicry of known and identified African birds such as *Dryoscopus cubla*. This would be an excellent example of hypermimicry, a term coined in [Shrike mimicks warbler mimicking shrike](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/20900).

This is the same individual as the one in XC572385.

As timed references still are so unreliable, I won't bother adding any yet. Check out the Forum Topic [Timing test](https://www.xeno-canto.org/442025) for more info on that subject.

Here are some cases of mimicry suggested by Magnus Wadstein:

14:25-14:35 sounds *Acrocephalus palustris* like, possibly with hypermimicry of *Melocichla mentalis*. 

03:57 and  21:32 sounds like *Dryoscopus cubla*.

C:a 10:50-10:55 sounds like *Dicrurus adsimilis*, but Magnus Wadstein suggests that these could be the asian species like *Dicrurus paradiseus* or  *Dicrurus hottentottus*.

This is a nocturnal recording of two song periods from a stationary bird; it has been seen and ID'ed earlier during the day (seeing the bird during night is obviously not possible). 

The habitat is farmland close to a small village; the bird is located inside a small patch of vegetation (an apple tree, an elder and a willow plus some lower vegetation) next to a small stream of water as marked on the map.

The first 45 seconds is the first song period, starting at 00:01:09 local time. The remaining recording is the second period, starting at 00:07:13 local time. Thus, approximately 5m19s has been removed from the recording; the bird was completely silent during the removed period.

The bird sings multiple different phrases but typically repeats them a couple of times with some variation between. Also prominent are the "ticks" and rattling sounds intermixed with more melodic singing.

The recording was done with a Røde VideoMic NTG using the built-in 48kHz/24-bit A/D converter and digitally stored on a OnePlus 5 mobile phone.

Subsequently a light amount of noise reduction, including low pass filtering with a 4th order Butterworth filter at 1.5 kHz, was performed; this has removed a slight amount of distant traffic noise.

Some frogs also appear in the recording...

rmk:
NEW VOCALIZATION !!!
At about two weeks of age, the juveniles have this sound, which one would not expect to come from an Acrocephalus. Here they call with the new call that is not known until now: a sharp "zitt" that is so high in pitch and so thin that it is difficult to perceive. It reminds of the sharp short sound that Coccothraustes coccothraustes utter in flight. The sharp sound is heard after 9 seconds of recording. This special sound is documented at the breeding’s in Dalarna in 2016 as well as in 2018.
A couple of juveniles are disturbed in the habitat and start to alarm at playback of song.

This recording is unmodified and starts about 25-minutes into a ca. 40 minute cassette recording. The habitat was scattered bushes and reeds bordering the lake and directly under overhead electricity cables. The birds song was not typical for the species and at the time there was discussion as to the birds identity although it has later been accepted by the Norwegian rare birds committee (NSKF).

This recording is unmodified and starts about eight minutes into a ca. 24 minute cassette recording which was made using a simple portable radio cassette player. The bird was heard and seen singing on 2nd July 1980 between 01:00 and 04:30 in a wet grassy habitat with scattered bushes under overhead electricity cables and during its stay the bird moved about a bit but was always found under these electricity cables. This was obviously a male and probably an adult although no plumage details of it being a second year was ever ascertained. The weather was fine but most of the recording was in darkness and no plumage details were recorded on this occasion.  This was the third accepted record for Norway and the first for Vestfold and bird was present from 29th June to 2nd July 1980 but was only seen and heard by a handfull of observers.

Singing from a willow tree, sitting fairly exposed around 3-4 meters up. Parabole mic recording from around 50 meters. Sunny weather. No filtering applied, the background "noise" comes from running water nearby. The imitations of a bell following 1:40 remind me of the Doppler effect that you hear when your train passes a road crossing. The bird could easily have heard something similar when passing a railway crossing in its flight.

XC377788, XC377803 and XC377804 are consecutive sections of the same continuous recording where two brief sections with traffic noise have been deleted. Original (.wav) file at: <http://soundcloud.com/user-370092153/zoom0033-4>.
